1
00:00:00,968 --> 00:00:02,668
Previously
on "The Good Doctor"...

2
00:00:02,703 --> 00:00:03,543
Ethan: How hard can it be

3
00:00:03,571 --> 00:00:06,441
to just act like
a normal human being?!

4
00:00:06,474 --> 00:00:07,644
[ Grunts ]
No!

5
00:00:07,675 --> 00:00:09,335
Stop petting
that stupid rabbit!

6
00:00:09,377 --> 00:00:11,447
[ Thud ]
We're never
going home again.

7
00:00:11,479 --> 00:00:13,109
We have each other,
and that's all we need.

8
00:00:13,147 --> 00:00:16,517
Shaun: My brother went to heaven
in front of my eyes.

9
00:00:18,319 --> 00:00:20,049
Steve: Never forget,
you're the smart one.

10
00:00:20,088 --> 00:00:22,158
And I'm proud of you,
Shaun.

11
00:00:22,190 --> 00:00:23,260
[ Television playing ]

12
00:00:23,291 --> 00:00:24,731
[ Knocking on door ]

13
00:00:24,758 --> 00:00:26,458
[ Birds chirping ]

14
00:00:26,494 --> 00:00:27,534
[ Knocking continues ]

15
00:00:27,561 --> 00:00:28,801
Kevin: Dad?

16
00:00:34,168 --> 00:00:35,798
Hey!

17
00:00:35,836 --> 00:00:37,206
Hey! [ Laughs ]

18
00:00:37,238 --> 00:00:38,138
I missed you, too!

19
00:00:38,172 --> 00:00:40,272
Oh, Penny, come.

20
00:00:40,308 --> 00:00:42,208
Stay.

21
00:00:42,243 --> 00:00:44,413
Hey, Dad.

22
00:00:44,445 --> 00:00:46,505
Sorry it's so early.
I just landed.

23
00:00:46,547 --> 00:00:48,477
Actually,
you're a bit late.

24
00:00:48,516 --> 00:00:49,676
Five weeks.

25
00:00:49,717 --> 00:00:52,817
I know.
I know.

26
00:00:52,853 --> 00:00:57,093
I'm sorry.
I-I-It's a long story, okay?

27
00:00:57,125 --> 00:00:58,785
But h-how was it?

28
00:00:58,826 --> 00:01:01,196
It was
your mother's funeral.

29
00:01:04,365 --> 00:01:05,725
Dad, I'm --

30
00:01:08,402 --> 00:01:09,402
[ Exhales sharply ]

31
00:01:15,443 --> 00:01:16,613
Okay.

32
00:01:16,644 --> 00:01:18,814
Well, um,
you have my cell number.

33
00:01:18,846 --> 00:01:21,746
It only works
if you answer it.

34
00:01:21,782 --> 00:01:23,422
[ Sighs ]

35
00:01:26,687 --> 00:01:28,787
[ Thumping, glass shattering ]

36
00:01:28,822 --> 00:01:30,392
Dad?

37
00:01:30,424 --> 00:01:31,864
Dad?!

38
00:01:31,892 --> 00:01:33,532
[ Wheezing ]
Dad!

39
00:01:33,561 --> 00:01:35,561
Hey, hey!
Hey -- you okay?

40
00:01:35,596 --> 00:01:37,326
You okay?
You can't breathe?!

41
00:01:37,365 --> 00:01:38,265
No? Okay.

42
00:01:38,299 --> 00:01:41,399
Hold on, I'm gonna call
for help, okay?

43
00:01:41,435 --> 00:01:42,765
911? My dad collapsed!

44
00:01:42,803 --> 00:01:44,473
He can't -- he can't breathe,
please hurry!

45
00:01:44,505 --> 00:01:45,605
Just hold on, Dad!

46
00:01:50,544 --> 00:01:53,214
[ Indistinct P.A. announcement ]

47
00:01:53,247 --> 00:01:54,747
Good morning, everyone!

48
00:01:54,782 --> 00:01:56,622
Right on time.
What, did you sleep here

49
00:01:56,650 --> 00:01:59,450
or use
a teleportation device?

50
00:01:59,487 --> 00:02:01,857
I used
a teleportation device.

51
00:02:01,889 --> 00:02:03,619
[ Laughs ]

52
00:02:03,657 --> 00:02:05,927
Nonsensical questions
usually imply sarcasm,

53
00:02:05,959 --> 00:02:08,659
which I've found people
often answer sarcastically.

54
00:02:08,696 --> 00:02:09,596
Good one.

55
00:02:09,630 --> 00:02:12,570
Trauma wants a consult
on a 66-year-old male

56
00:02:12,600 --> 00:02:14,770
who collapsed
from severe anaphylaxis,

57
00:02:14,802 --> 00:02:16,842
complicated
by respiratory arrest.

58
00:02:16,870 --> 00:02:18,470
His son just got back
from Thailand.

59
00:02:18,506 --> 00:02:20,566
Almost immediately, the father
had his allergic reaction.

60
00:02:20,608 --> 00:02:22,808
Merrill: [ Groaning ]

61
00:02:22,843 --> 00:02:24,413
Patient has
a few allergies --

62
00:02:24,445 --> 00:02:25,745
pollen, mold, shellfish --

63
00:02:25,779 --> 00:02:27,819
but no corresponding allergens
were in evidence.

64
00:02:27,848 --> 00:02:30,348
Why are we doing a
surgical consult on an allergy?

65
00:02:30,384 --> 00:02:31,794
Well, we're not.
We're doing a consult

66
00:02:31,819 --> 00:02:33,949
on the excruciating
abdominal pain he now has.

67
00:02:33,987 --> 00:02:37,257
[ Groaning loudly ]

68
00:02:37,291 --> 00:02:39,661
As you may have heard.

69
00:02:39,693 --> 00:02:43,333
Mr. Wilks, hi,
I'm Dr. Neil Melendez.

70
00:02:43,364 --> 00:02:45,204
Heard you had
some abdominal pain.

71
00:02:45,233 --> 00:02:53,343
**

72
00:02:53,374 --> 00:03:01,554
**

73
00:03:01,582 --> 00:03:09,692
**

74
00:03:09,723 --> 00:03:10,763
-- Captions by VITAC --

75
00:03:10,791 --> 00:03:19,971
**

76
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:21,640
The guy
was in some serious pain --

77
00:03:21,669 --> 00:03:23,299
10 milligrams
of morphine worth.

78
00:03:23,337 --> 00:03:24,907
Test results show
elevated lipase,

79
00:03:24,938 --> 00:03:26,838
amylase,
pancreatic enzymes.

80
00:03:26,874 --> 00:03:27,844
Pancreas is enlarged.

81
00:03:27,875 --> 00:03:30,535
Could be pancreatitis,
maybe alcohol-induced.

82
00:03:30,578 --> 00:03:31,948
The son said he smelled alcohol
on his father

83
00:03:31,979 --> 00:03:32,909
at 6:00 in the morning.

84
00:03:32,946 --> 00:03:35,246
And anaphylaxis has been known
to precipitate

85
00:03:35,283 --> 00:03:36,923
attacks of pancreatitis.

86
00:03:36,950 --> 00:03:38,490
Guess that's it, then.

87
00:03:40,554 --> 00:03:42,494
Meaning
you totally disagree.

88
00:03:42,523 --> 00:03:44,333
Not everyone who starts
their day off with a Mimosa

89
00:03:44,358 --> 00:03:46,488
fries their pancreas.

90
00:03:46,527 --> 00:03:47,857
Your eyesight must a
hell of a lot better than mine.

91
00:03:47,895 --> 00:03:49,855
Because I can't see
the entire pancreas

92
00:03:49,897 --> 00:03:51,797
due to the overlying
bowel gas.

93
00:03:54,435 --> 00:03:56,795
We'll order an abdominal CT
and take a better look.

94
00:03:56,837 --> 00:03:58,437
There you go.

95
00:03:58,472 --> 00:03:59,912
Where the hell is Murphy?

96
00:03:59,940 --> 00:04:01,540
It's a severe fracture,

97
00:04:01,575 --> 00:04:03,305
but I don't think
you'll need pins.

98
00:04:03,344 --> 00:04:05,014
Young bones tend to heal
very well.

99
00:04:05,045 --> 00:04:08,875
Young Bones? Isn't that
a "Star Trek: Origins"
graphic novel?

100
00:04:11,585 --> 00:04:14,015
I'm not sure.

101
00:04:14,054 --> 00:04:15,564
No, that was a joke.

102
00:04:15,589 --> 00:04:16,859
Where are your parents?

103
00:04:16,890 --> 00:04:18,730
They're coming.
They both work in the city,

104
00:04:18,759 --> 00:04:20,559
so it's a long drive
for them.

105
00:04:20,594 --> 00:04:22,464
I was on
a school field trip,

106
00:04:22,496 --> 00:04:23,856
and I tripped
over my own feet.

107
00:04:23,897 --> 00:04:26,697
Of course, it was
right in front of Shelby Lomar.

108
00:04:26,734 --> 00:04:28,004
At least
it was pretty gross,

109
00:04:28,035 --> 00:04:30,435
so I got some sympathy points
for that.

110
00:04:33,541 --> 00:04:34,981
I would expect this
to have been caused

111
00:04:35,008 --> 00:04:36,778
by a more serious
accident.

112
00:04:36,810 --> 00:04:37,910
Nope, just a trip.

113
00:04:37,945 --> 00:04:39,045
I do that a lot.

114
00:04:39,079 --> 00:04:40,049
What can I say?

115
00:04:40,080 --> 00:04:41,650
I'm clumsy.

116
00:04:41,682 --> 00:04:43,682
Yes. Now follow my finger.

117
00:04:43,717 --> 00:04:50,057
**

118
00:04:50,090 --> 00:04:51,560
You have
some nystagmus --

119
00:04:51,592 --> 00:04:53,662
an involuntary eye movement.

120
00:04:53,694 --> 00:04:55,764
So what's that mean?

121
00:04:55,796 --> 00:04:57,696
When you fell,
did you hit your head?

122
00:04:57,731 --> 00:04:58,801
No.

123
00:04:58,832 --> 00:05:00,002
What, you think I have
brain damage?

124
00:05:00,033 --> 00:05:02,903
Nystagmus can be a sign
of a neurological issue.

125
00:05:02,936 --> 00:05:03,736
Oh.

126
00:05:03,771 --> 00:05:05,071
Well, that would explain
the "C" I got

127
00:05:05,105 --> 00:05:07,905
in social studies.

128
00:05:07,941 --> 00:05:10,341
That was another joke,
wasn't it?

129
00:05:10,378 --> 00:05:12,448
Mm.

130
00:05:12,480 --> 00:05:14,720
I'm going to order
a head CT for you.

131
00:05:14,748 --> 00:05:16,078
Go for it.

132
00:05:18,952 --> 00:05:20,622
Shaun,
are you getting any sleep?

133
00:05:20,654 --> 00:05:21,994
Yes.
Really?

134
00:05:22,022 --> 00:05:23,592
I mean,
really getting sleep?

135
00:05:23,624 --> 00:05:24,864
I got here on time.

136
00:05:24,892 --> 00:05:25,862
Well, that's good.

137
00:05:25,893 --> 00:05:28,133
I used
a teleportation device.

138
00:05:28,161 --> 00:05:32,731
**

139
00:05:32,766 --> 00:05:34,936
Radiology form, please.

140
00:05:34,968 --> 00:05:40,038
**

141
00:05:40,073 --> 00:05:41,743
Shaun, that boy,
he looks like --

142
00:05:41,775 --> 00:05:42,905
Steve.

143
00:05:42,943 --> 00:05:44,413
He does.

144
00:05:44,445 --> 00:05:45,875
Is he related?

145
00:05:45,913 --> 00:05:48,783
His name is Evan Gallico,
so I don't think so.

146
00:05:51,084 --> 00:05:52,754
Wow. That is uncanny.

147
00:05:52,786 --> 00:05:54,086
Just coincidental.

148
00:05:54,121 --> 00:05:56,461
He looks
exactly like your brother.

149
00:05:56,490 --> 00:05:57,490
No, he doesn't.

150
00:05:57,525 --> 00:05:59,385
His hair is shorter.

151
00:05:59,427 --> 00:06:01,087
It freaks me out.
It doesn't freak you out?

152
00:06:01,128 --> 00:06:02,728
No.

153
00:06:02,763 --> 00:06:03,533
It's okay if it does --

154
00:06:03,564 --> 00:06:05,834
No, he's not Steve.
Steve's dead.

155
00:06:10,203 --> 00:06:12,813
"I used a teleportation device"
was a joke.

156
00:06:14,742 --> 00:06:16,882
Yeah,
that's...that's good.

157
00:06:19,780 --> 00:06:22,950
[ Indistinct P.A. announcement ]

158
00:06:25,653 --> 00:06:28,063
Kevin: So, I couldn't come
to Mom's funeral

159
00:06:28,088 --> 00:06:30,488
because I fell in love.

160
00:06:32,560 --> 00:06:34,090
She was another teacher
at the school.

161
00:06:34,127 --> 00:06:36,427
A Thai woman.

162
00:06:36,464 --> 00:06:37,734
And she was kind
and --

163
00:06:37,765 --> 00:06:42,065
and beautiful
and loving...

164
00:06:42,102 --> 00:06:45,012
and very, very sick.

165
00:06:45,038 --> 00:06:47,678
She had
a congenital heart defect.

166
00:06:53,113 --> 00:06:57,053
Look, if you don't want
to tell me where you've been

167
00:06:57,084 --> 00:06:58,694
for the last six months,
then don't.

168
00:06:58,719 --> 00:06:59,749
It's your business.

169
00:06:59,787 --> 00:07:01,617
But don't insult
my intelligence.

170
00:07:01,655 --> 00:07:02,985
Well, I couldn't
just leave her.

171
00:07:03,023 --> 00:07:04,533
You couldn't leave her
for five minutes

172
00:07:04,558 --> 00:07:05,558
to make a phone call?

173
00:07:05,593 --> 00:07:07,563
[ Knocking on door ]

174
00:07:07,595 --> 00:07:09,125
This a bad time?

175
00:07:09,162 --> 00:07:12,702
No, come in.

176
00:07:16,937 --> 00:07:18,067
According to the CT,

177
00:07:18,105 --> 00:07:19,565
you have a lesion
on your pancreas.

178
00:07:19,607 --> 00:07:21,037
Well, what do you think
this lesion could be?

179
00:07:21,074 --> 00:07:21,814
Not sure.

180
00:07:21,842 --> 00:07:23,882
That's why we need
to biopsy it.

181
00:07:23,911 --> 00:07:25,911
It could
just be a benign cyst.

182
00:07:25,946 --> 00:07:26,806
Or...?

183
00:07:26,847 --> 00:07:29,217
Or...

184
00:07:29,249 --> 00:07:32,249
it could be cancer,
right?

185
00:07:32,285 --> 00:07:33,945
We'll know soon enough.

186
00:07:33,987 --> 00:07:42,697
**

187
00:07:42,730 --> 00:07:50,870
**

188
00:07:50,904 --> 00:07:52,514
This won't take long.

189
00:07:52,540 --> 00:07:54,240
Evan: I know.
I've had two of these.

190
00:07:54,274 --> 00:07:55,984
One more
and I get my Scout badge.

191
00:07:56,009 --> 00:07:57,879
[ Chuckles ]

192
00:08:00,548 --> 00:08:01,618
That was funny.

193
00:08:01,649 --> 00:08:03,249
Tough to tell
without looking at you,

194
00:08:03,283 --> 00:08:05,753
but I'm guessing
that was sarcasm.

195
00:08:05,786 --> 00:08:07,786
No. I have autism,

196
00:08:07,821 --> 00:08:11,021
which makes it hard
for me to read social cues.

197
00:08:11,058 --> 00:08:12,188
Jokes are difficult.

198
00:08:12,225 --> 00:08:14,895
I used to know a kid
with autism. Peter.

199
00:08:14,928 --> 00:08:18,798
He was kind of weird
but super nice.

200
00:08:18,832 --> 00:08:20,272
Used to know?

201
00:08:20,300 --> 00:08:22,140
You don't know him
anymore?

202
00:08:22,169 --> 00:08:23,739
He died.

203
00:08:23,771 --> 00:08:25,971
Hit by a car.

204
00:08:26,006 --> 00:08:28,636
You know anyone
who died?

205
00:08:28,676 --> 00:08:30,176
My brother.

206
00:08:30,210 --> 00:08:31,550
That sucks.

207
00:08:34,982 --> 00:08:37,052
Why did you have
the other CT scans?

208
00:08:37,084 --> 00:08:39,324
My parents have...

209
00:08:39,352 --> 00:08:41,592
uh, what's the word
for fear of getting sick?

210
00:08:41,622 --> 00:08:43,192
Hypochondriasis?

211
00:08:43,223 --> 00:08:45,133
Mm, no, worse than that.

212
00:08:45,158 --> 00:08:47,898
They have...nosophobia.

213
00:08:47,928 --> 00:08:49,798
I love that word.

214
00:08:49,830 --> 00:08:52,730
What do you think
of Miss Gannett?

215
00:08:52,766 --> 00:08:53,866
She's nice.

216
00:08:53,901 --> 00:08:56,871
I think
she's callipygian.

217
00:08:56,904 --> 00:08:58,274
She's what?

218
00:08:58,305 --> 00:08:59,665
Callipygian?

219
00:08:59,707 --> 00:09:02,637
It means "having
shapely buttocks," Shaun.

220
00:09:02,676 --> 00:09:03,776
Duh.

221
00:09:06,246 --> 00:09:07,946
You read the dictionary.

222
00:09:07,981 --> 00:09:10,951
What it lacks in plot,
it makes up for in vocab.

223
00:09:10,984 --> 00:09:13,724
So, you married?

224
00:09:13,754 --> 00:09:15,964
Girlfriend?

225
00:09:15,989 --> 00:09:17,689
Boyfriend?

226
00:09:17,725 --> 00:09:19,055
Tropical fish?

227
00:09:21,261 --> 00:09:22,831
I like Lea.

228
00:09:22,863 --> 00:09:24,973
Ooh. And who's Lea?

229
00:09:24,998 --> 00:09:26,168
Lea is a friend.

230
00:09:26,199 --> 00:09:28,169
A friend you date?

231
00:09:28,201 --> 00:09:30,241
A friend with benefits?

232
00:09:30,270 --> 00:09:32,970
I lend her batteries
sometimes.

233
00:09:33,006 --> 00:09:34,006
I like
where this is going...

234
00:09:34,041 --> 00:09:35,311
[ Machine beeps ]

235
00:09:38,411 --> 00:09:41,081
So, you know,
keep going.

236
00:09:41,114 --> 00:09:43,354
'Cause if you don't,
I will.

237
00:09:43,383 --> 00:09:45,053
It's kind of my thing,
you know?

238
00:09:45,085 --> 00:09:47,215
Just constant talking --
annoys everyone.

239
00:09:47,254 --> 00:09:49,664
Murphy.
Well,
I guess not everyone.

240
00:09:49,690 --> 00:09:51,790
Hey.
My family's pretty
used to me now. I mean...

241
00:09:51,825 --> 00:09:52,825
Hey.
[ Button clicks, beeps ]

242
00:09:52,860 --> 00:09:55,760
...my friends are
very talkative as well, so...

243
00:09:55,796 --> 00:09:57,296
You're giving
the fractured arm a head CT?

244
00:09:57,330 --> 00:09:58,800
Yes.
Get back
to the pancreas.

245
00:09:58,832 --> 00:09:59,732
He's not clumsy.

246
00:09:59,767 --> 00:10:02,597
He has a brain tumor
behind the inner ear.

247
00:10:04,838 --> 00:10:06,268
Forget the pancreas.

248
00:10:13,246 --> 00:10:15,246
Mr. and Mrs. Gallico?

249
00:10:15,282 --> 00:10:16,782
Hi.
Hi.

250
00:10:16,817 --> 00:10:18,017
I'm Dr. Shaun Murphy.

251
00:10:18,051 --> 00:10:19,151
I'm treating your son.

252
00:10:19,186 --> 00:10:20,216
Well, how is he?

253
00:10:20,253 --> 00:10:21,693
We were told
it was a bad break,

254
00:10:21,722 --> 00:10:23,262
but it should heal
no problem.

255
00:10:23,290 --> 00:10:24,960
I know why Evan tripped.

256
00:10:24,992 --> 00:10:27,802
He had a tumor
in the temporal bone
behind his left ear,

257
00:10:27,828 --> 00:10:29,328
which is affecting
his balance.

258
00:10:29,362 --> 00:10:32,072
I've arranged for a consult
with Dr. Najid in oncology

259
00:10:32,099 --> 00:10:33,669
and she's going --
No, that won't be necessary.

260
00:10:33,701 --> 00:10:35,141
We --

261
00:10:35,168 --> 00:10:37,198
We already have
an oncologist.

262
00:10:37,237 --> 00:10:39,067
[ Sighs ]

263
00:10:39,106 --> 00:10:42,436
Evan's been diagnosed
with stage four osteosarcoma.

264
00:10:42,475 --> 00:10:44,435
He was complaining
of a sore shin.

265
00:10:44,477 --> 00:10:48,317
The last thing that we expected
was bone cancer.

266
00:10:48,348 --> 00:10:49,678
The doctors at SFM,

267
00:10:49,717 --> 00:10:52,147
they gave him
a year to live.

268
00:10:55,188 --> 00:10:57,958
That was seven months ago.

269
00:10:57,991 --> 00:11:01,261
Osteosarcoma explains
the severity of his fracture --

270
00:11:01,294 --> 00:11:03,834
he will need pins in his arm
after all.

271
00:11:03,864 --> 00:11:05,104
Uh, can we see him?

272
00:11:05,132 --> 00:11:07,402
Yes. He's in room 414.

273
00:11:07,434 --> 00:11:09,274
Uh, Dr. Murphy?

274
00:11:11,772 --> 00:11:15,112
He doesn't know
about his diagnosis.

275
00:11:15,142 --> 00:11:18,852
We would really like
to keep it that way.

276
00:11:18,879 --> 00:11:22,319
**

277
00:11:28,889 --> 00:11:29,819
He's the patient.

278
00:11:29,857 --> 00:11:31,857
Doesn't he have the right
to know the truth?

279
00:11:31,892 --> 00:11:32,762
Well, no.

280
00:11:32,793 --> 00:11:35,133
He's also a minor,
so, no, he doesn't.

281
00:11:35,162 --> 00:11:36,402
Evan's
very intelligent --

282
00:11:36,429 --> 00:11:37,359
he'd be able
to handle it.

283
00:11:37,397 --> 00:11:40,067
Well, Shaun,
maybe it's not just about Evan.

284
00:11:40,100 --> 00:11:43,000
Maybe it's about his parents,
as well.

285
00:11:43,036 --> 00:11:46,906
Maybe it's just too difficult
for them to tell Evan right now.

286
00:11:46,940 --> 00:11:47,840
I don't know.

287
00:11:47,875 --> 00:11:49,235
Then they're the ones
who shouldn't be told.

288
00:11:49,276 --> 00:11:50,906
Well, let me ask you this,
Shaun --

289
00:11:50,944 --> 00:11:53,954
what's so wrong
about Evan being allowed

290
00:11:53,981 --> 00:11:56,521
to enjoy as much of his life
as possible?

291
00:11:56,549 --> 00:11:58,319
Evan wants to know
the truth.

292
00:11:58,351 --> 00:11:59,491
How do you know that?

293
00:12:03,824 --> 00:12:07,264
If this were Steve,
if this were your brother,

294
00:12:07,294 --> 00:12:08,504
would he want to know
the truth?

295
00:12:08,528 --> 00:12:10,028
Is that what this is?

296
00:12:15,102 --> 00:12:17,372
Dad's such a tool.

297
00:12:17,404 --> 00:12:18,414
I found
my birthday present --

298
00:12:18,438 --> 00:12:20,368
in their closet,
right where they always hide it.

299
00:12:20,407 --> 00:12:21,337
I was just about
to open it

300
00:12:21,374 --> 00:12:23,544
when Dad caught me snooping
and freaked out.

301
00:12:23,576 --> 00:12:26,906
I hate
all that phony surprise stuff.

302
00:12:26,947 --> 00:12:29,917
It's an
AquaBlast Water Cannon.

303
00:12:29,950 --> 00:12:32,150
I was with Mom
when she bought it.

304
00:12:32,185 --> 00:12:33,415
Thank you, Shaun.

305
00:12:33,453 --> 00:12:35,423
Your honesty's refreshing!

306
00:12:38,959 --> 00:12:42,229
Yes, he would want to know
the truth.

307
00:12:42,262 --> 00:12:44,902
Well, there's nothing
we can do about it.

308
00:12:44,932 --> 00:12:46,902
It's not your decision --
it's theirs.

309
00:12:46,934 --> 00:12:48,304
He's their son.

310
00:12:50,070 --> 00:12:55,510
**

311
00:12:55,542 --> 00:12:56,342
[ Door beeps ]

312
00:12:56,376 --> 00:12:57,906
[ Sighs ]

313
00:12:57,945 --> 00:13:03,515
**

314
00:13:03,550 --> 00:13:04,890
Claire, I need you.

315
00:13:06,854 --> 00:13:08,324
Sure, what's up?

316
00:13:10,057 --> 00:13:12,227
I need someone
to lie for me.

317
00:13:12,259 --> 00:13:15,199
Okay...

318
00:13:15,228 --> 00:13:17,028
I'm flattered?

319
00:13:20,533 --> 00:13:23,403
Hey, doc?

320
00:13:23,436 --> 00:13:26,066
There's something
I need to tell my dad.

321
00:13:26,106 --> 00:13:29,106
We haven't moved him.
He's still in room, uh, 326.

322
00:13:31,979 --> 00:13:35,249
Do you have
a medical question for me?

323
00:13:35,282 --> 00:13:36,622
Is he dying?

324
00:13:36,649 --> 00:13:38,089
We don't know yet.

325
00:13:38,118 --> 00:13:40,088
The biopsy
will tell us more.

326
00:13:40,120 --> 00:13:41,220
Okay.

327
00:13:45,558 --> 00:13:47,388
My dad is a good guy.

328
00:13:49,662 --> 00:13:53,902
We've just never been
on the same page, you know?

329
00:13:53,934 --> 00:13:57,344
My mother was the one
that I could talk to --

330
00:13:57,370 --> 00:14:00,070
same for him.

331
00:14:00,107 --> 00:14:04,137
So, without her,

332
00:14:04,177 --> 00:14:06,377
we're both pretty useless.

333
00:14:12,319 --> 00:14:14,519
Room 326.

334
00:14:14,554 --> 00:14:15,364
Right.

335
00:14:15,388 --> 00:14:22,558
**

336
00:14:22,595 --> 00:14:24,625
Dr. Murphy called me in
for a second opinion.

337
00:14:24,664 --> 00:14:29,174
Um, you need some pins
in your arm.

338
00:14:29,202 --> 00:14:30,142
Why?

339
00:14:30,170 --> 00:14:31,570
What's changed?

340
00:14:31,604 --> 00:14:33,944
Well, after studying
the radiology report,

341
00:14:33,974 --> 00:14:35,414
given how bad
the break is,

342
00:14:35,442 --> 00:14:37,412
we just think it would be
a prudent step

343
00:14:37,444 --> 00:14:40,614
to ensure an efficient and
thorough mending to the break.

344
00:14:40,647 --> 00:14:42,947
Will I be able
to play baseball again?

345
00:14:42,983 --> 00:14:44,353
Well, I don't see why not,

346
00:14:44,384 --> 00:14:45,624
once it's completely healed,

347
00:14:45,652 --> 00:14:47,322
after some physiotherapy.

348
00:14:47,354 --> 00:14:49,094
How long
before I can pitch?

349
00:14:49,122 --> 00:14:50,962
It's hard to say.

350
00:14:50,991 --> 00:14:53,031
[ Monitor beeping ]

351
00:14:56,997 --> 00:14:58,997
He wanted someone to lie
for him.

352
00:14:59,032 --> 00:15:03,442
[ Scoffs ]
And he picked you.

353
00:15:03,470 --> 00:15:05,410
Merrill's son asked
for personal advice.

354
00:15:05,438 --> 00:15:06,538
And he picked you.

355
00:15:06,573 --> 00:15:08,283
I know, right?
[ Scoffs ]

356
00:15:08,308 --> 00:15:11,638
He's lying to his dad
about something.

357
00:15:11,678 --> 00:15:13,248
Yeah? What?

358
00:15:13,280 --> 00:15:14,610
I don't know.

359
00:15:14,647 --> 00:15:16,177
You didn't ask?

360
00:15:16,216 --> 00:15:19,686
It didn't seem relevant,
medically.

361
00:15:19,719 --> 00:15:22,589
You know it's not that difficult
to be a human being.

362
00:15:22,622 --> 00:15:25,062
Just tell him
to "come clean,"

363
00:15:25,092 --> 00:15:27,392
"honesty
is the best policy,"

364
00:15:27,427 --> 00:15:30,027
"a lie is a stone
in your heart."

365
00:15:30,063 --> 00:15:31,363
Who said the last one?

366
00:15:31,398 --> 00:15:32,668
Me.

367
00:15:32,699 --> 00:15:33,699
I made it up.

368
00:15:33,733 --> 00:15:34,633
Hmm.

369
00:15:34,667 --> 00:15:37,367
[ Chuckles ]

370
00:15:37,404 --> 00:15:40,014
And...I got it.

371
00:15:42,309 --> 00:15:43,379
[ Beeping quickens ]
He's anaphylactic.

372
00:15:43,410 --> 00:15:44,310
Would you get me an epi?
I'm coming out.

373
00:15:44,344 --> 00:15:46,384
The throat's constricting.
Pull the tube.

374
00:15:46,413 --> 00:15:49,153
[ Gasping ]

375
00:15:49,182 --> 00:15:51,322
[ Saw whirring ]

376
00:15:54,721 --> 00:15:56,291
[ Whirring stops ]

377
00:15:59,526 --> 00:16:03,556
So, what's up
with "Dr. Browne"?

378
00:16:03,596 --> 00:16:07,196
She's Lea, isn't she?

379
00:16:07,234 --> 00:16:08,244
Claire is my colleague.

380
00:16:08,268 --> 00:16:12,638
Oh, come on, I saw the way
you were looking at her.

381
00:16:12,672 --> 00:16:13,742
How?

382
00:16:16,143 --> 00:16:17,783
I don't think
I look like that.

383
00:16:17,810 --> 00:16:21,110
Okay, so then why'd you
call her in for a "consult"?

384
00:16:21,148 --> 00:16:23,478
Mm...

385
00:16:23,516 --> 00:16:25,616
Okay.

386
00:16:25,652 --> 00:16:29,262
Yes, she's better at talking
to people than I am.

387
00:16:29,289 --> 00:16:32,759
Wow. I counted
like 50 tells there.

388
00:16:32,792 --> 00:16:35,262
You really suck
at lying.
I know.

389
00:16:35,295 --> 00:16:37,495
Too bad.
It's an important social skill.

390
00:16:39,632 --> 00:16:42,472
So how do you know
when to lie?

391
00:16:42,502 --> 00:16:44,142
When people
need to know things,

392
00:16:44,171 --> 00:16:45,111
they need to know.

393
00:16:45,138 --> 00:16:46,508
If they don't,

394
00:16:46,539 --> 00:16:48,379
lie through your teeth
and feel good about it.

395
00:16:48,408 --> 00:16:49,778
What if they need
to know the truth,

396
00:16:49,809 --> 00:16:51,279
but it'll hurt them?

397
00:16:54,714 --> 00:16:58,054
Some can handle it,
some can't.

398
00:16:58,085 --> 00:17:00,385
So how do you know
who can and who can't?

399
00:17:00,420 --> 00:17:01,550
You tell the truth.

400
00:17:01,588 --> 00:17:04,218
If they like you after,
then you'll know.

401
00:17:04,257 --> 00:17:05,457
If they don't?

402
00:17:05,492 --> 00:17:08,162
Then it doesn't really matter
anyway.

403
00:17:13,200 --> 00:17:14,470
You have cancer.

404
00:17:16,136 --> 00:17:19,206
[ Sighs ]

405
00:17:19,239 --> 00:17:22,379
Yeah, I know.

406
00:17:30,717 --> 00:17:32,717
My parents took me in
for a sore leg.

407
00:17:32,752 --> 00:17:34,222
After a whole bunch
of tests,

408
00:17:34,254 --> 00:17:35,364
they talked
to the doctor,

409
00:17:35,388 --> 00:17:37,558
then came out
and told me I was fine.

410
00:17:37,590 --> 00:17:40,660
That's it.
Just "fine."

411
00:17:40,693 --> 00:17:44,333
The next day,
they bought me a PS4.

412
00:17:44,364 --> 00:17:46,574
So I Googled my symptoms,

413
00:17:46,599 --> 00:17:48,839
and I narrowed it down
to osteosarcoma

414
00:17:48,868 --> 00:17:50,538
or growing pains.

415
00:17:50,570 --> 00:17:53,640
Kids don't get gaming systems
for growing pains.

416
00:17:55,542 --> 00:17:59,312
Hey, it's okay.

417
00:18:01,681 --> 00:18:03,251
I'm not afraid to die.

418
00:18:03,283 --> 00:18:04,683
You're not?

419
00:18:04,717 --> 00:18:06,687
Well, I mean,
the dying part will suck

420
00:18:06,719 --> 00:18:10,419
if it hurts, but...

421
00:18:10,457 --> 00:18:12,657
I'm not afraid
about the actual death part.

422
00:18:12,692 --> 00:18:15,362
Because you believe
you're going to Heaven?

423
00:18:15,395 --> 00:18:16,825
Because I don't.

424
00:18:19,632 --> 00:18:21,202
If I believe in Heaven,

425
00:18:21,234 --> 00:18:22,604
then I got to believe
in God,

426
00:18:22,635 --> 00:18:25,165
then I got to believe
God made me sick.

427
00:18:25,205 --> 00:18:27,535
How messed up is that?

428
00:18:27,574 --> 00:18:31,284
It's just easier to think
that it's all random

429
00:18:31,311 --> 00:18:33,351
and when it's over,

430
00:18:33,380 --> 00:18:38,190
it's just...

431
00:18:38,218 --> 00:18:39,348
over.

432
00:18:44,457 --> 00:18:46,627
So what about Lea?

433
00:18:46,659 --> 00:18:48,759
Where'd you guys meet?

434
00:18:48,795 --> 00:18:50,425
In the hallway.

435
00:18:54,567 --> 00:18:55,767
That's a beautiful story.

436
00:18:55,802 --> 00:18:57,202
Yes.

437
00:18:57,237 --> 00:18:58,807
She's my neighbor.

438
00:18:58,838 --> 00:19:01,608
Convenient.

439
00:19:01,641 --> 00:19:03,341
He had
another allergic reaction.

440
00:19:03,376 --> 00:19:05,806
The pancreas?
Merrill Wilks, yeah.

441
00:19:05,845 --> 00:19:08,415
And the second attack
was even more severe
than the first.

442
00:19:08,448 --> 00:19:10,518
It coincided with biopsying
the pancreatic lesion,

443
00:19:10,550 --> 00:19:11,850
which now appears
was a cyst.

444
00:19:11,884 --> 00:19:12,854
Well, now we know
he's allergic

445
00:19:12,885 --> 00:19:14,185
to whatever's
in that cyst.

446
00:19:14,221 --> 00:19:15,691
We also that
the next cyst that pops

447
00:19:15,722 --> 00:19:17,762
will probably kill him.
Well, if there is a next.

448
00:19:17,790 --> 00:19:18,690
Let's run a couple tests,

449
00:19:18,725 --> 00:19:20,485
see if there's any evidence
of parasites.

450
00:19:20,527 --> 00:19:21,757
And MRI his entire body --

451
00:19:21,794 --> 00:19:23,234
if we're lucky,
he only had the two cysts

452
00:19:23,263 --> 00:19:24,363
and he can go home.

453
00:19:28,368 --> 00:19:30,238
Are you looking
for loopholes?

454
00:19:30,270 --> 00:19:31,600
Hoping to save Evan?

455
00:19:31,638 --> 00:19:33,738
Everyone makes mistakes.

456
00:19:33,773 --> 00:19:34,943
Which means you should
double-check

457
00:19:34,974 --> 00:19:36,644
every file
in the hospital.

458
00:19:36,676 --> 00:19:40,676
The oncologist flagged
his neutrophil count of 634

459
00:19:40,713 --> 00:19:41,783
as low.

460
00:19:41,814 --> 00:19:42,724
That is low.

461
00:19:42,749 --> 00:19:43,619
Low normal.

462
00:19:43,650 --> 00:19:46,390
I can still hear
the word "low" in there.

463
00:19:46,419 --> 00:19:47,789
Mm.

464
00:19:50,957 --> 00:19:52,857
He's just a kid.

465
00:19:52,892 --> 00:19:55,962
I know how hard it is
to think of him dying.

466
00:19:55,995 --> 00:19:58,465
He's okay with that.

467
00:19:58,498 --> 00:19:59,968
I find that
hard to believe.

468
00:19:59,999 --> 00:20:01,329
We all die --

469
00:20:01,368 --> 00:20:03,538
if we accepted that,
we'd be happier.

470
00:20:03,570 --> 00:20:07,970
Maybe. But we're not good
with contentment.

471
00:20:08,007 --> 00:20:10,477
Fighting death
is what keeps us alive.

472
00:20:10,510 --> 00:20:11,710
[ Computer beeps ]

473
00:20:11,744 --> 00:20:17,324
**

474
00:20:17,350 --> 00:20:18,820
Okay.

475
00:20:20,052 --> 00:20:21,792
We got a hit --
Echinococcus.

476
00:20:21,821 --> 00:20:23,561
Jared: Echinococcus?

477
00:20:23,590 --> 00:20:24,690
The cysts are filled
with tapeworms?

478
00:20:24,724 --> 00:20:26,334
Cysts?
There are more?

479
00:20:26,359 --> 00:20:27,889
Three more?
Four more.

480
00:20:27,927 --> 00:20:29,357
You missed the one
in his brain.

481
00:20:29,396 --> 00:20:32,566
**

482
00:20:32,599 --> 00:20:34,429
[ Knocking on door ]
Jared: Dr. Glassman?

483
00:20:34,467 --> 00:20:35,637
Yeah?

484
00:20:35,668 --> 00:20:37,338
You used to be a neurosurgeon,
right?

485
00:20:37,370 --> 00:20:38,670
So they say.

486
00:20:38,705 --> 00:20:39,935
Take this, will you?

487
00:20:41,974 --> 00:20:43,284
I need one.

488
00:20:43,310 --> 00:20:44,480
Who would you recommend?

489
00:20:44,511 --> 00:20:45,881
What you got?

490
00:20:51,784 --> 00:20:53,454
Wow, that's cool.

491
00:20:56,022 --> 00:20:58,462
How the hell did I get tapeworms
in my head?

492
00:20:58,491 --> 00:21:00,461
No idea, but you do.

493
00:21:00,493 --> 00:21:02,663
You can pick up the eggs
from coyotes or wolves.

494
00:21:02,695 --> 00:21:04,695
You been hanging around
coyotes or wolves?

495
00:21:04,731 --> 00:21:05,931
I live
in the suburbs --

496
00:21:05,965 --> 00:21:07,465
we don't even have
a petting zoo.

497
00:21:07,500 --> 00:21:09,900
You might've had these cysts
for quite some time.

498
00:21:09,936 --> 00:21:11,336
When one of them burst,

499
00:21:11,371 --> 00:21:13,471
that's what caused
the first allergic reaction.

500
00:21:13,506 --> 00:21:15,436
Well, why did it burst?

501
00:21:15,475 --> 00:21:16,875
Why did it burst?

502
00:21:16,909 --> 00:21:20,479
Any sudden movements, twists,
turns, squeeze.

503
00:21:20,513 --> 00:21:21,513
A hug?

504
00:21:21,548 --> 00:21:24,448
Could be.

505
00:21:24,484 --> 00:21:26,554
But you weren't there
for the second one.

506
00:21:28,688 --> 00:21:31,018
I punctured the cyst
on your pancreas

507
00:21:31,057 --> 00:21:32,557
during the biopsy.

508
00:21:32,592 --> 00:21:35,332
As you've seen,
allergic reactions get worse

509
00:21:35,362 --> 00:21:36,162
each time they happen.

510
00:21:36,195 --> 00:21:37,555
So a third one,
that would be bad.

511
00:21:37,597 --> 00:21:38,967
That would be...
[ Chuckles ]

512
00:21:38,998 --> 00:21:39,868
That would be very bad.

513
00:21:39,899 --> 00:21:42,029
So we're gonna have
to surgically remove

514
00:21:42,068 --> 00:21:44,368
all the cysts intact.

515
00:21:44,404 --> 00:21:46,574
Dr. Glassman's
one of the most highly acclaimed

516
00:21:46,606 --> 00:21:47,606
neurosurgeons
in the state.

517
00:21:47,640 --> 00:21:48,810
You are very lucky
to have him.

518
00:21:48,841 --> 00:21:52,951
And Dr. Kalu is fast becoming
a very accomplished flatterer.

519
00:21:52,979 --> 00:21:56,049
The cranial cyst,
that is a big deal.

520
00:21:56,082 --> 00:21:58,652
We're gonna have to take off
the top of your skull.

521
00:21:58,685 --> 00:22:00,715
You'd be digging in
to my brain?

522
00:22:00,753 --> 00:22:02,093
Well, yeah, pretty much.

523
00:22:02,121 --> 00:22:02,961
With saline.

524
00:22:02,989 --> 00:22:04,959
We use it to gently displace
the cyst,

525
00:22:04,991 --> 00:22:07,361
and then, poof,
it magically pops out.

526
00:22:07,394 --> 00:22:08,564
Kind of like
delivering a baby.

527
00:22:08,595 --> 00:22:11,055
You know,
if childbirth were painless.

528
00:22:11,097 --> 00:22:14,467
And then we move on
to the other cysts.

529
00:22:14,501 --> 00:22:16,671
Hey, we're gonna take
good care of you.

530
00:22:16,703 --> 00:22:25,953
**

531
00:22:25,978 --> 00:22:35,458
**

532
00:22:35,488 --> 00:22:44,698
**

533
00:22:44,731 --> 00:22:53,971
**

534
