**

535
00:23:03,550 --> 00:23:12,790
**

536
00:23:12,825 --> 00:23:21,865
**

537
00:23:21,901 --> 00:23:23,971
Evan doesn't have cancer.

538
00:23:30,577 --> 00:23:31,477
* Cowards cowering in concrete
showers in Rikers Island *

539
00:23:31,511 --> 00:23:32,481
* Victims, we the wolves
that's wilding *

540
00:23:32,512 --> 00:23:33,252
* We often smilin'
at sights of violence *

541
00:23:33,279 --> 00:23:34,279
* Acting brave and courageous

542
00:23:34,313 --> 00:23:36,753
* Ain't advantageous
for health and safety *

543
00:23:36,783 --> 00:23:38,123
* So when we say
"run the jewels" *

544
00:23:38,150 --> 00:23:39,820
It might not be cancer!

545
00:23:39,852 --> 00:23:41,592
* And that goes
for a guy or lady *

546
00:23:41,621 --> 00:23:43,591
It might not be cancer!

547
00:23:43,623 --> 00:23:45,693
[ Music stops ]

548
00:23:45,725 --> 00:23:47,455
Look at you on time --
two for two.

549
00:23:47,494 --> 00:23:49,004
It might not be cancer.

550
00:23:49,028 --> 00:23:51,098
Fractured arm?
Yes.

551
00:23:51,130 --> 00:23:53,630
You said he'd been diagnosed
with stage four osteosarcoma.

552
00:23:53,666 --> 00:23:56,466
Evan was diagnosed with the flu
eight months ago,

553
00:23:56,503 --> 00:23:57,943
but his symptoms were actually
a better fit

554
00:23:57,970 --> 00:23:59,010
with Epstein-Barr virus,

555
00:23:59,038 --> 00:24:01,168
which is linked to
Langerhans cell histiocytosis,

556
00:24:01,207 --> 00:24:02,807
which causes
osteolytic lesions

557
00:24:02,842 --> 00:24:04,182
in the long bones
of the upper limbs.

558
00:24:04,210 --> 00:24:05,980
And those lesions
could be misdiagnosed

559
00:24:06,012 --> 00:24:07,152
as signs
of osteosarcoma.

560
00:24:07,179 --> 00:24:08,779
Yes.
What about
his brain tumor?

561
00:24:08,815 --> 00:24:12,515
Langerhans can also manifest
in the skull.

562
00:24:12,552 --> 00:24:13,852
Instead of
a death sentence,

563
00:24:13,886 --> 00:24:15,046
he could have something
that could easily

564
00:24:15,087 --> 00:24:16,017
be treated
with prednisone?

565
00:24:16,055 --> 00:24:18,585
Next, we need to do
a bone-marrow aspiration

566
00:24:18,625 --> 00:24:19,685
to confirm.

567
00:24:19,726 --> 00:24:20,956
I assume
you've looked at his file.

568
00:24:20,993 --> 00:24:22,063
For a very long time.

569
00:24:22,094 --> 00:24:23,504
Well, there must've been
a biopsy.

570
00:24:23,530 --> 00:24:24,700
What did
the pathology report say?

571
00:24:24,731 --> 00:24:26,001
Yes.
There were two biopsies.

572
00:24:26,032 --> 00:24:29,702
Both were positive
for osteosarcoma.

573
00:24:29,736 --> 00:24:32,666
Murphy...
They could be
false positives.

574
00:24:32,705 --> 00:24:34,035
Do you have any idea
how unlikely it is

575
00:24:34,073 --> 00:24:35,113
to have
two false positives?

576
00:24:35,141 --> 00:24:36,141
0.3%.

577
00:24:36,175 --> 00:24:37,975
Which we can comfortably
round off to "not likely."

578
00:24:38,010 --> 00:24:39,510
It is possible --

579
00:24:39,546 --> 00:24:41,646
Yes, but it means telling
the parents of a dying child

580
00:24:41,681 --> 00:24:45,051
that there's hope,
when really there isn't.

581
00:24:45,084 --> 00:24:46,824
Grab a shower
and get ready for rounds.

582
00:24:53,626 --> 00:24:55,086
Glassman:
Wow. [ Chuckles ]

583
00:24:55,127 --> 00:24:56,597
Imaginative and creative.

584
00:24:56,629 --> 00:24:57,359
Yes.

585
00:24:57,396 --> 00:24:58,766
What are the chances
you're right?

586
00:24:58,798 --> 00:24:59,868
0.3%.

587
00:24:59,899 --> 00:25:01,069
330 to 1.

588
00:25:01,100 --> 00:25:03,770
333 to 1.

589
00:25:03,803 --> 00:25:05,303
You really think
that it's worth

590
00:25:05,337 --> 00:25:07,007
putting Evan's parents
through all this?

591
00:25:07,039 --> 00:25:08,169
Of course.

592
00:25:08,207 --> 00:25:10,607
If we did this
333 times,

593
00:25:10,643 --> 00:25:12,913
we'd be giving false hope
to 332 people

594
00:25:12,945 --> 00:25:14,275
for approximately
four hours,

595
00:25:14,313 --> 00:25:15,723
and we'd save one life.

596
00:25:15,748 --> 00:25:18,148
Isn't that worth it?
[ Exhales sharply ]

597
00:25:18,184 --> 00:25:19,794
Anyway, Dr. Melendez
won't let me

598
00:25:19,819 --> 00:25:21,219
ask for consent to test.

599
00:25:21,253 --> 00:25:24,123
What if I don't tell them
what I'm doing?

600
00:25:24,156 --> 00:25:26,326
A blatant ethics violation --
that's your solution?

601
00:25:26,358 --> 00:25:27,628
Yes.

602
00:25:27,660 --> 00:25:29,160
How do I do that?

603
00:25:31,363 --> 00:25:33,973
[ Scoffs ]

604
00:25:34,000 --> 00:25:36,000
Well, uh, [chuckles],

605
00:25:36,035 --> 00:25:38,705
you do it
and then don't tell anyone.

606
00:25:38,738 --> 00:25:40,108
No one.
If anyone asks...

607
00:25:40,139 --> 00:25:42,709
your attending noticed
a low RBC count

608
00:25:42,742 --> 00:25:43,842
and needed to find
the cause --

609
00:25:43,876 --> 00:25:47,576
that's it --
no biggie.

610
00:25:47,614 --> 00:25:48,084
Hmm.

611
00:25:48,114 --> 00:25:54,124
**

612
00:25:54,153 --> 00:25:55,893
[ Coughs ]

613
00:25:57,957 --> 00:26:01,127
You know Wilks' Grocery
on Santa Clara 17th?

614
00:26:01,160 --> 00:26:04,300
It's been an institution
for nearly 60 years.

615
00:26:04,330 --> 00:26:07,370
My grandparents
started it in 1958,

616
00:26:07,399 --> 00:26:10,069
and my wife and I took it over
in '82.

617
00:26:10,102 --> 00:26:11,202
But when my wife got sick

618
00:26:11,237 --> 00:26:13,707
and I started talking to Kevin
about taking it over,

619
00:26:13,740 --> 00:26:16,240
he just...took off.

620
00:26:18,077 --> 00:26:19,347
To him,
it was just a place

621
00:26:19,378 --> 00:26:21,648
to sell lettuce
and toilet paper.

622
00:26:24,784 --> 00:26:29,664
My father chairs a real-estate
development company in the U.K.

623
00:26:29,689 --> 00:26:30,889
Thought I'd be
the perfect person

624
00:26:30,923 --> 00:26:32,633
to set up
the U.S. office.

625
00:26:32,659 --> 00:26:34,989
You wanted to be in
the "helping profession," hmm?

626
00:26:35,027 --> 00:26:37,757
I wanted to be
in my profession.

627
00:26:37,797 --> 00:26:40,197
It's not about how small
or how big the venture is,

628
00:26:40,232 --> 00:26:42,132
it's about doing something
that's yours.

629
00:26:45,204 --> 00:26:46,714
I guess.

630
00:26:52,979 --> 00:26:55,849
When he was little,
we were inseparable.

631
00:26:55,882 --> 00:26:58,322
[ Chuckles ]

632
00:26:58,350 --> 00:27:03,020
Ah, he used to love
to come to the store to "work."

633
00:27:03,055 --> 00:27:06,055
[ Laughs ]

634
00:27:06,092 --> 00:27:08,032
I even had a little apron
made for him --

635
00:27:08,060 --> 00:27:10,430
had his name on it, too.

636
00:27:10,462 --> 00:27:13,732
Still, you know,
kids...

637
00:27:13,766 --> 00:27:16,036
grow up.

638
00:27:16,068 --> 00:27:20,038
I'm just grateful that he stayed
close to his mother.

639
00:27:20,072 --> 00:27:24,442
He could talk to her,
tell her anything.

640
00:27:24,476 --> 00:27:27,306
[ Voice breaking ]
So could I.

641
00:27:27,346 --> 00:27:29,746
And when she went...

642
00:27:29,782 --> 00:27:31,152
[ Sobs ]

643
00:27:35,021 --> 00:27:38,061
...I lost them both.

644
00:27:38,090 --> 00:27:40,130
Looks like he's back now.

645
00:27:40,159 --> 00:27:45,969
All I know is he ditched me
when I needed him.

646
00:27:45,998 --> 00:27:49,798
Well, you know,
as a wise person once said,

647
00:27:49,836 --> 00:27:53,966
"holding a grudge is a stone
in your heart."

648
00:27:54,006 --> 00:27:56,776
[ Sighs deeply ]

649
00:27:59,345 --> 00:28:00,345
What's that for?

650
00:28:00,379 --> 00:28:03,879
Local anaesthetic
for a bone-marrow aspiration.

651
00:28:03,916 --> 00:28:07,746
Why do I need
a bone-marrow aspiration?

652
00:28:07,787 --> 00:28:09,717
My attending saw
a low RBC count

653
00:28:09,756 --> 00:28:12,256
and wants
to find the cause --

654
00:28:12,291 --> 00:28:14,031
no biggie.

655
00:28:14,060 --> 00:28:15,260
"No biggie"?

656
00:28:15,294 --> 00:28:16,904
You're lying.

657
00:28:16,929 --> 00:28:18,969
What's going on?

658
00:28:18,998 --> 00:28:21,198
You already told me
I have terminal cancer,

659
00:28:21,233 --> 00:28:22,873
what's worse than that?

660
00:28:27,974 --> 00:28:29,244
You might not.

661
00:28:31,477 --> 00:28:33,147
It might not be
osteosarcoma --

662
00:28:33,179 --> 00:28:35,919
might be
Langerhans cell histiocytosis,

663
00:28:35,948 --> 00:28:37,778
which is treatable.

664
00:28:37,817 --> 00:28:38,817
Treatable?

665
00:28:38,851 --> 00:28:41,051
As in,
I might not die?

666
00:28:41,087 --> 00:28:42,517
That's why
I need to aspirate --

667
00:28:42,554 --> 00:28:43,924
to find out for sure.

668
00:28:43,956 --> 00:28:45,386
Do my parents know?

669
00:28:45,424 --> 00:28:49,404
Mm...I was told not
to get their hopes up.

670
00:28:49,428 --> 00:28:53,528
Then let's do it
before they get back.

671
00:28:53,565 --> 00:28:55,495
Roll onto your side.

672
00:28:55,534 --> 00:29:00,874
**

673
00:29:00,907 --> 00:29:06,147
**

674
00:29:06,178 --> 00:29:08,248
Is there a Scout badge
for aspirations?

675
00:29:08,280 --> 00:29:09,320
[ Chuckles ]

676
00:29:09,348 --> 00:29:10,978
I think someone
just made a joke.

677
00:29:14,854 --> 00:29:15,494
Hello.

678
00:29:15,521 --> 00:29:16,461
What are you doing?

679
00:29:16,488 --> 00:29:17,388
Painkiller.

680
00:29:17,423 --> 00:29:20,093
My arm hurts.

681
00:29:20,126 --> 00:29:20,986
That wouldn't explain

682
00:29:21,027 --> 00:29:23,357
why I'd be injecting
your lumbar region.

683
00:29:27,967 --> 00:29:29,467
Okay. Yes, hello.

684
00:29:29,501 --> 00:29:33,911
I think Evan may have been
misdiagnosed with cancer.

685
00:29:33,940 --> 00:29:37,010
I think he has something
that creates bone lesions

686
00:29:37,043 --> 00:29:38,383
that look like
osteosarcoma.

687
00:29:38,410 --> 00:29:40,380
It's a small chance, 0.3%,
but I --

688
00:29:40,412 --> 00:29:44,252
You -- You told Evan
that he has cancer?

689
00:29:44,283 --> 00:29:45,993
And now
you are telling him -- and us --

690
00:29:46,018 --> 00:29:46,718
that he doesn't?

691
00:29:46,752 --> 00:29:48,192
I'm telling you
he might not.

692
00:29:48,220 --> 00:29:50,190
That's why I need
to perform this aspiration.

693
00:29:50,222 --> 00:29:52,162
He says whatever I have
might be treatable.

694
00:29:52,191 --> 00:29:53,131
Are you insane?

695
00:29:53,159 --> 00:29:54,289
No. I am not insane.

696
00:29:54,326 --> 00:29:55,356
I thought you'd be happy.

697
00:29:55,394 --> 00:29:56,864
There is a significant link
between

698
00:29:56,896 --> 00:29:58,396
Langerhans cell histiocytosis
and --

699
00:29:58,430 --> 00:30:00,300
Go! Get out!

700
00:30:00,332 --> 00:30:02,232
[ Coughing ]

701
00:30:02,935 --> 00:30:04,395
Let me get you some water.

702
00:30:04,436 --> 00:30:06,206
[ Coughing continues ]

703
00:30:06,238 --> 00:30:09,608
[ Breathing sharply ]

704
00:30:09,641 --> 00:30:10,881
-Oh, my God!
-Hands right here --

705
00:30:10,910 --> 00:30:12,340
-[ Coughing ]
-Right here!

706
00:30:12,378 --> 00:30:13,278
Respiratory, stat!

707
00:30:17,049 --> 00:30:19,349
**

708
00:30:19,385 --> 00:30:21,215
He has a massive embolus,

709
00:30:21,253 --> 00:30:23,263
probably thrown
from his fracture.

710
00:30:23,289 --> 00:30:24,889
It's located
at the bifurcation

711
00:30:24,924 --> 00:30:26,334
of the pulmonary arteries.

712
00:30:26,358 --> 00:30:27,958
He's close
to hemodynamic collapse.

713
00:30:27,994 --> 00:30:29,164
Yeah, no kidding.

714
00:30:29,195 --> 00:30:30,855
I'd like to assist.

715
00:30:30,897 --> 00:30:32,097
Not a chance.

716
00:30:32,131 --> 00:30:35,101
Okay.
I'd like to assist.

717
00:30:35,134 --> 00:30:36,474
You're obviously
too close to the case.

718
00:30:36,502 --> 00:30:38,642
I think I'm just
the right amount of close.

719
00:30:38,670 --> 00:30:40,240
Murphy,
you lied to the parents

720
00:30:40,272 --> 00:30:42,142
just so you could try
to prove your ridiculous theory.

721
00:30:42,174 --> 00:30:45,954
You're too damn close.

722
00:30:45,978 --> 00:30:47,478
Saddle embolism,
scrub in.

723
00:30:47,513 --> 00:30:55,053
**

724
00:30:55,087 --> 00:30:56,887
Melendez: We have to get rid of
the embolus before he arrests.

725
00:30:56,923 --> 00:30:58,563
His heart
is barely pumping blood.

726
00:30:58,590 --> 00:31:00,260
I can feel
the pulmonary artery...

727
00:31:00,292 --> 00:31:02,532
I just need to find
the obstruction...there!

728
00:31:02,561 --> 00:31:03,431
I got it.

729
00:31:03,462 --> 00:31:05,032
Knife.

730
00:31:05,064 --> 00:31:06,404
EKG is showing
right heart strain.

731
00:31:06,432 --> 00:31:07,502
He can't take this
much longer.

732
00:31:07,533 --> 00:31:09,073
I know, but if I move
any quicker,

733
00:31:09,101 --> 00:31:10,501
I could nick
the left main artery

734
00:31:10,536 --> 00:31:11,566
and kill the boy.

735
00:31:11,603 --> 00:31:16,913
**

736
00:31:16,943 --> 00:31:19,283
The phrase "no biggie"
gave me away.

737
00:31:19,311 --> 00:31:21,411
You really got to learn
how to lie, Shaun.

738
00:31:23,449 --> 00:31:25,079
Am I in trouble?

739
00:31:25,117 --> 00:31:27,517
Yes.

740
00:31:27,553 --> 00:31:29,663
Unless you're right.

741
00:31:29,688 --> 00:31:31,558
If I'm wrong,
they shouldn't be upset.

742
00:31:31,590 --> 00:31:36,030
They know
it's highly unlikely.

743
00:31:36,062 --> 00:31:38,232
False hope, Shaun...

744
00:31:38,264 --> 00:31:40,204
it's just plain cruel.

745
00:31:40,232 --> 00:31:48,272
**

746
00:31:48,307 --> 00:31:56,317
**

747
00:31:56,348 --> 00:31:58,618
Hey.

748
00:31:58,650 --> 00:32:01,590
He talk to you?

749
00:32:01,620 --> 00:32:03,490
Did you talk to him?

750
00:32:03,522 --> 00:32:05,262
I don't know
what to tell him.

751
00:32:10,596 --> 00:32:12,256
You love your father,
don't you?

752
00:32:12,298 --> 00:32:13,628
Yeah, of course.

753
00:32:13,665 --> 00:32:16,035
Right. Well, he's about to go
in for brain surgery.

754
00:32:16,068 --> 00:32:18,098
There's huge risks involved.

755
00:32:18,137 --> 00:32:19,237
Whatever this lie is,

756
00:32:19,271 --> 00:32:20,311
can you live
the rest of your life

757
00:32:20,339 --> 00:32:22,009
knowing you kept it
from him?

758
00:32:34,520 --> 00:32:38,260
My -- My girlfriend
wasn't sick.

759
00:32:38,290 --> 00:32:40,360
Okay? She dumped me.

760
00:32:40,392 --> 00:32:41,662
She's married
with two kids --

761
00:32:41,693 --> 00:32:44,233
had no intention
of leaving them.

762
00:32:44,263 --> 00:32:45,263
I-I was an idiot.

763
00:32:45,297 --> 00:32:48,067
You got your heart broken,
that's the problem here?

764
00:32:48,100 --> 00:32:49,670
No -- no, Dad.

765
00:32:49,701 --> 00:32:50,671
The problem is...

766
00:32:50,702 --> 00:32:51,772
[ Sighs ]

767
00:32:51,803 --> 00:32:53,273
I didn't run away
to Thailand

768
00:32:53,305 --> 00:32:58,505
because I thought
Wilks' Grocery was beneath me.

769
00:32:58,544 --> 00:33:00,614
I was afraid
that I would never be able

770
00:33:00,646 --> 00:33:04,516
to fill your shoes...

771
00:33:04,550 --> 00:33:07,020
And then
I proved myself right.

772
00:33:07,053 --> 00:33:15,063
**

773
00:33:15,094 --> 00:33:23,144
**

774
00:33:23,169 --> 00:33:25,069
Left pulmonary artery's
open.

775
00:33:25,104 --> 00:33:26,214
Ring Forceps.

776
00:33:26,238 --> 00:33:32,638
**

777
00:33:32,678 --> 00:33:34,008
Come on.

778
00:33:36,648 --> 00:33:38,078
Got it.

779
00:33:39,518 --> 00:33:41,318
[ Exhales softly ]

780
00:33:41,353 --> 00:33:43,193
EKG is normalizing.

781
00:33:43,222 --> 00:33:44,192
He's okay.

782
00:33:44,223 --> 00:33:45,623
Nice job.

783
00:33:45,657 --> 00:33:47,557
All right,
flush the left pulmonary artery

784
00:33:47,593 --> 00:33:48,563
and close him up.

785
00:33:48,594 --> 00:33:49,604
Okay.

786
00:33:49,628 --> 00:33:55,828
**

787
00:33:55,867 --> 00:33:58,767
Um...Dr. Melendez...

788
00:33:58,804 --> 00:34:00,544
Take a look at this.

789
00:34:00,572 --> 00:34:07,182
**

790
00:34:07,213 --> 00:34:13,623
**

791
00:34:28,800 --> 00:34:33,170
Recycling --
Shaun, very responsible.

792
00:34:33,205 --> 00:34:35,405
It's a book.

793
00:34:35,441 --> 00:34:36,681
I appreciate that.

794
00:34:45,317 --> 00:34:46,487
[ Chuckles ]

795
00:34:46,518 --> 00:34:47,788
Thanks, Shaun.

796
00:34:49,688 --> 00:34:51,458
[ Door opens ]

797
00:34:59,398 --> 00:35:02,168
Melendez:
We got the embolism.

798
00:35:02,201 --> 00:35:05,801
He's in recovery
and he's doing fine.

799
00:35:05,837 --> 00:35:07,267
But while we were
in there,

800
00:35:07,306 --> 00:35:09,236
we did find
something else.

801
00:35:09,275 --> 00:35:11,105
Lesions on his ribs.

802
00:35:14,413 --> 00:35:17,553
Irrefutable proof
of osteosarcoma.

803
00:35:17,583 --> 00:35:19,793
It's metastasized
to his chest cavity.

804
00:35:22,388 --> 00:35:24,288
I'm sorry.

805
00:35:24,790 --> 00:35:28,360
[ Sighs ]

806
00:35:28,394 --> 00:35:30,234
[ Sniffles ]

807
00:35:30,262 --> 00:35:33,172
[ Sobbing ]

808
00:35:33,199 --> 00:35:34,829
I'm very sorry.

809
00:35:40,506 --> 00:35:47,806
**

810
00:35:47,846 --> 00:35:55,346
**

811
00:35:55,387 --> 00:35:59,727
Glassman: Give that
a nice, warm saline bath.

812
00:35:59,758 --> 00:36:02,728
Forceps and Taylor scissors,
please.

813
00:36:02,761 --> 00:36:03,801
Thank you.

814
00:36:03,829 --> 00:36:12,899
**

815
00:36:12,938 --> 00:36:14,308
Look at that.

816
00:36:14,340 --> 00:36:16,280
That's what built
the pyramids,

817
00:36:16,308 --> 00:36:19,208
painted the Mona Lisa,

818
00:36:19,245 --> 00:36:21,905
invented the Internet.

819
00:36:21,947 --> 00:36:23,417
[ Exhales sharply ]

820
00:36:23,449 --> 00:36:26,389
There is our interloper.

821
00:36:26,418 --> 00:36:28,488
Squeezeball please,
Deidre.

822
00:36:28,520 --> 00:36:29,590
Squeezeball?

823
00:36:29,621 --> 00:36:31,761
His name for it,
not ours.

824
00:36:31,790 --> 00:36:35,960
The saline gently displaces
the cyst

825
00:36:35,994 --> 00:36:38,404
and coaxes it out
of its little hiding place --

826
00:36:38,430 --> 00:36:43,640
Hopefully in one piece
so we don't have to call 911.

827
00:36:43,669 --> 00:36:45,699
Come on, now...

828
00:36:45,737 --> 00:36:47,967
Tray, please.

829
00:36:48,006 --> 00:36:49,636
There we go...

830
00:36:49,675 --> 00:36:52,305
A little bit more...

831
00:36:52,344 --> 00:36:54,354
And there we go.

832
00:36:54,380 --> 00:36:55,650
Got it.

833
00:36:55,681 --> 00:36:56,621
[ Exhales ]

834
00:36:56,648 --> 00:36:58,518
He has his father's eyes.

835
00:36:58,550 --> 00:37:00,290
That was incredible.

836
00:37:00,319 --> 00:37:02,319
One down,
three to go...

837
00:37:02,354 --> 00:37:08,464
**

838
00:37:08,494 --> 00:37:14,604
**

839
00:37:14,633 --> 00:37:17,003
Hey.
There he is.

840
00:37:17,035 --> 00:37:19,835
Hi, Sweetie.

841
00:37:19,871 --> 00:37:21,541
What's the matter?

842
00:37:21,573 --> 00:37:22,613
Nothing.

843
00:37:22,641 --> 00:37:25,941
We're just happy
you did so great.

844
00:37:27,746 --> 00:37:30,576
You had
what's called an embolism.

845
00:37:30,616 --> 00:37:32,876
It clogged an artery
in your lungs.

846
00:37:32,918 --> 00:37:35,488
But the good news
is they got it.

847
00:37:35,521 --> 00:37:38,361
And you're gonna be
just fine.

848
00:37:38,390 --> 00:37:39,460
Still...

849
00:37:39,491 --> 00:37:41,591
too bad
about the cancer, huh?

850
00:37:41,627 --> 00:37:42,727
No, no, no, no.

851
00:37:42,761 --> 00:37:44,731
The doctor did not know
what he was talking about --

852
00:37:44,763 --> 00:37:46,673
Dad, I know all about it.

853
00:37:46,698 --> 00:37:50,338
I have for a long time.

854
00:37:50,369 --> 00:37:52,299
[ Inhales deeply ]
I --

855
00:37:55,807 --> 00:37:58,477
I am so sorry.

856
00:37:58,510 --> 00:38:01,050
It's okay.

857
00:38:01,079 --> 00:38:03,349
[ Sniffling ]

858
00:38:03,382 --> 00:38:11,622
**

859
00:38:13,425 --> 00:38:16,555
Because I'm not
gonna be alone.

860
00:38:17,996 --> 00:38:21,396
Grandma's gonna be there,
too.

861
00:38:21,433 --> 00:38:25,043
Auntie Arlene.

862
00:38:25,070 --> 00:38:28,440
Uncle Jim, if he figured out
how to stop swearing.

863
00:38:28,474 --> 00:38:30,544
[ Chuckles ]

864
00:38:30,576 --> 00:38:32,736
[ Chuckles ]

865
00:38:32,778 --> 00:38:34,878
[ Clears throat ]

866
00:38:34,913 --> 00:38:36,583
I'll get you some water,
buddy.

867
00:38:36,615 --> 00:38:41,915
**

868
00:38:41,953 --> 00:38:47,493
**

869
00:38:47,526 --> 00:38:49,796
So, I took Penny
for a walk --

870
00:38:49,828 --> 00:38:51,398
just around the block.

871
00:38:53,699 --> 00:38:56,499
And I picked her up
some of those rawhide treats,

872
00:38:56,535 --> 00:38:59,635
you know...

873
00:38:59,671 --> 00:39:01,741
the ones that Mom
used to like to give to her.

874
00:39:08,046 --> 00:39:10,016
[ Voice breaking ]
I miss her, Dad.

875
00:39:10,048 --> 00:39:17,618
**

876
00:39:17,656 --> 00:39:24,996
**

877
00:39:25,030 --> 00:39:32,100
**

878
00:39:32,137 --> 00:39:39,477
**

879
00:39:39,511 --> 00:39:40,811
Evan: Coast is clear?

880
00:39:40,846 --> 00:39:47,046
**

881
00:39:47,085 --> 00:39:48,045
Yes.

882
00:39:48,086 --> 00:39:50,186
Thank you.

883
00:39:50,221 --> 00:39:51,891
Mm, I was wrong.

884
00:39:51,923 --> 00:39:53,063
You tried.

885
00:39:53,091 --> 00:39:54,591
I was wrong.

886
00:39:56,462 --> 00:39:57,832
Your parents hate me.

887
00:39:57,863 --> 00:39:58,833
I know.

888
00:39:58,864 --> 00:40:01,074
I gave you false hope.
Yeah.

889
00:40:01,099 --> 00:40:03,869
But for a minute there,
it was pretty awesome.

890
00:40:06,872 --> 00:40:08,912
I'm going to ask you
for a favor.

891
00:40:11,510 --> 00:40:14,210
Well, I'm not giving away
my Make-A-Wish.

892
00:40:14,245 --> 00:40:16,745
Mm, would you mind
if I read you something?

893
00:40:16,782 --> 00:40:18,652
It's not long.

894
00:40:18,684 --> 00:40:20,654
That I can do.

895
00:40:30,161 --> 00:40:32,731
"Atticus was right.

896
00:40:32,764 --> 00:40:35,204
One time he said
you never really know a man

897
00:40:35,233 --> 00:40:38,903
until you stand in his shoes
and walk around in them.

898
00:40:38,937 --> 00:40:41,707
Just standing
on the Radley porch was enough.

899
00:40:41,740 --> 00:40:43,040
The streetlights were fuzzy

900
00:40:43,074 --> 00:40:45,714
from the fine rain
that was falling"...

901
00:40:45,744 --> 00:40:49,114
**

902
00:40:49,147 --> 00:40:57,717
* I can't protect you
from the course of life *

903
00:40:57,756 --> 00:41:05,056
* But you know me
and you know I was born to try *

904
00:41:05,096 --> 00:41:12,596
* It's just the symptom
of a middle-aged attack *

905
00:41:12,638 --> 00:41:15,068
..."'Atticus,
he was real nice.'

906
00:41:15,106 --> 00:41:16,536
His hands
were under my chin,

907
00:41:16,575 --> 00:41:17,805
pulling up the cover,

908
00:41:17,843 --> 00:41:20,053
tucking it around me.

909
00:41:20,078 --> 00:41:23,518
'Most people are, Scout,
when you finally see them.'

910
00:41:23,549 --> 00:41:26,749
He turned out the light
and went into Jem's room.

911
00:41:26,785 --> 00:41:28,545
He would be there
all night,

912
00:41:28,587 --> 00:41:32,017
and he would be there when Jem
waked up in the morning."

913
00:41:32,057 --> 00:41:36,997
**

914
00:41:37,028 --> 00:41:39,568
Sounds like a good book.

915
00:41:39,598 --> 00:41:41,728
Could've used a spoiler alert,
though.

916
00:41:41,767 --> 00:41:49,037
**

917
00:41:49,074 --> 00:41:51,044
Thank you.

918
00:41:51,076 --> 00:41:55,146
* Confusing you,
from what you need *

919
00:41:55,180 --> 00:41:59,150
* Every hand that you hold

920
00:41:59,184 --> 00:42:00,854
* It comes back

921
00:42:00,886 --> 00:42:03,116
That's all.

922
00:42:03,154 --> 00:42:07,234
* Every word, every ride

923
00:42:07,258 --> 00:42:11,798
* It comes back every time

924
00:42:11,830 --> 00:42:15,200
**

925
00:42:15,233 --> 00:42:19,743
* It comes back every time

926
00:42:19,771 --> 00:42:24,881
**

927
00:42:24,910 --> 00:42:25,940
* Every time

